description.text:
UPDATES:

1) A lighted version of this thing is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1784381.

Have you been searching in vain for an animated Halloween pumpkin bracelet for the upcoming Halloween parties (and who isn't)? Well Motorized Halloween Pumpkin Bracelet might be the Thingiverse thing for you!

Motorized Halloween Pumpkin Bracelet includes two bracelet styles. The first is a rigid bracelet style that can, with moderate heating from a handheld hairdryer, be slightly adjusted to wrap around the wrist. The second is a watch strap style and is designed for a 19mm wide by 3mm thick one piece velcro watch strap. This style accommodates more wrist sizes.

In both styles, a 6vdc battery pack (4 1.5vdc AA cells with on/off switch) is wired to the motor with enough wire to fit up a sleeve and into a pocket. A newer version will follow with on board batteries.

Video of prototype Motorized Halloween Pumpkin Bracelet in vise is here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ubg8rI712io.

Video of prototype Motorized Halloween Pumpkin Bracelet on my wrist is here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ADwiCzazJRs.

Designed using Sketchup Make 2016 and printed in PLA on an Ultimaker 2 Extended.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Resolution:

.1mm

Infill:

20

Notes:

When printing "Gear Crown.stl", supports may be required.

Parts I Purchased:

1) Gear Motor: DC 6V 60 RPM High Torque Electric Replacement Gear Box Motor (Amazon).

2) Battery Holder: Plastic On/Off Switch 4 x 1.5V AA Battery Case Holder w Cap Black (Amazon).

3) Batteries: 4 AA batteries.

4) Velcro one piece watch band (19mm wide, 3mm thick) (Walmart).

5) 26 gauge red stranded wire.

6) 26 gauge black stranded wire.

Printing:

Print 2 "Pin.stl". Print 1 of either "Bracelet.stl" or "Bracelet Strap.stl". Print 1 each of the remaining pieces.

When printing "Gear Crown.stl", supports may be required depending on your printer, printer settings and color.

Assembly:

Prior to assembly, test fit and trim, file, sand, etc. all parts as necessary for smooth movement of moving surfaces, and tight fit for non moving surfaces. Depending on the colors you chose and your printer settings, more or less trimming, filing and/or sanding will be required. If the tight fitting components are too loose, add a small dot of cyanoacrylate to each side of the pin, allow to dry completely (I use accelerator to speed the process), then try the fit again. Repeat until tight.

Assemble as per "Assembly.stl". I perform the assembly task in the following order:

1) Press "Gear Motor.stl" onto the motor.

2) Slide the motor & gear assembly into "Bracelet.stl".

3) Press two "Pin.stl" into "Gear Crown.stl".

4) Using "Axle.stl", attach the gear crown assembly to "Bracelet.stl". The gear crown assembly should rotate freely on the axle.

5) Attach "Base Pumpkin.stl" to the gear crown assembly by sliding the pin heads into the large holes in "Base Pumpkin.stl", then rotating "Base Pumpkin.stl" counter clockwise (as viewed from the top) to secure it in place on the gear crown assembly.

6) Press "Stem Pumpkin.stl" into "Lid Pumpkin.stl".

7) Attach the lid assembly to "Base Pumpkin.stl".

8) Solder the battery holder positive (red) terminal to the motor positive terminal, with extension as required to reach from a pocket to the bracelet. Solder the battery holder negative (black) terminal to the motor negative terminal, also with extension as required to reach from a pocket to the bracelet.

Place the assembly on your wrist and turn it on. Hope you make one!

description.text:
The camping kit, consist of three (3) basic parts:
 The Fork
 The Spoon
 The Tongs
Each part can be used separately, providing its own use, or they can be combined all together.
The whole idea, started by the need to carry as less as possible during camping. This kit provides six (6) different functions with only three (3) parts.

Characteristics
All parts are designed with particular attention to be lightweight, use as less material as possible, occupy little space and to be able to be printed to a home use 3D printer.
The basic characteristic although is that can be combined with easy find, everyday things. By this way, we reach our goal for less material usage, and smaller parts.
The material suggested is ABS, as is the most durable 3D printing material, easy to find, and food friendly.

Technical & printing characteristics:

-FORK
Weight: 4.86 gr
*Layers: 845
**Material cost: 0.15 €
Printing time: 1h & 52 min

-SPOON
Weight: 7.49 gr
*Layers: 841
**Material cost: 0.22 €
Printing time: 2h & 42 min

-TONGS
Weight: 7.97 gr
*Layers: 55
**Material cost: 0.24 €
Printing time: 2h & 04 min

*Layer thickness estimated 0.125 mm.
** Material used: ABS.

Printing suggestion (Look at the image - Assembly in a box 12x12x12cm)

It is suggested to use this kind of placement for the parts when printing. By this way users are able to print them with the least support material, and minimize printing time. The box in the picture is approximately 12x12x12 cm, the dimensions of a home use 3D printer.

title: Autoquad.95 - 95mm micro brushed scisky quadcopter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Autoquad.95

With max motor spacing of just under 95mm, the autoquad is a slightly trapezoidal frame with the front motors spaced a bit wider than the rear. I like the way trap-quads handle at speed, so I made this model to be able to tweak the spacing and add/remove stiffeners until i figured out what 'feels' best. The final decision (final. hah.) is 72mm front motors, 68mm rear motors, and stiffening bars on the back only.

Designed for 8.5mm motors and the micro scisky FC. The Scisky press fits perfectly, and small tabs in the controller bay hold the FC level by supporting it from flat places on the chip.

Uploaded two frame files, one has the motor cutouts at 8.5mm and the other at 8.6 - the motor bays are decagons to aid in press fitting. If printing in ABS, be sure to scale up a little bit to account for shrinkage if needed. I print in ABS with the "tight fit" model at 1.02 scale, 45mm/s, 0.3 layer height.

The battery bay mounts on either the top or the bottom and is designed for turnigy 600mah 1s 35C batteries, the long skinny kind. Inner dims 29mm wide and 8.5mm tall. Attach a piece of rubber band across the gap cutout, poke holes in the band where the screws go through and mount the battery bay and the band together with two screws. A perfect battery holder for less weight than a strap. I'll be making more bays to accommodate different battery styles.

title: Freedom: The Underground Railroad Slave Catcher Pawns

description.text:
Early editions of Academy Games "Freedom: The Underground Railroad" included wooden pawns in the five shapes (triangle, square, circle, oval, pentagon). Later and current editions simply include a cardboard token to represent these figures.

I wanted to make something more unique than a simple extruded shape for use in the game, so I designed these. The base has Roman column design with the shape set atop each. Each shape is a different color as follows: (oval = purple, pentagon = blue, triangle = yellow, square = brown, circle = orange). These correspond to the die rolled in game to control movement of these pawns.

Printer:

Micro3D

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Medium

Infill:

Hollow, Thick Walls

Notes:

Used white PLA from BAMTACK at 210 degrees C.

Painting

I left the layered look, no smoothing and primed mine with artist gesso. I painted each of the columns in a gunmetal gray, then drybrushed on a metallic copper. The bases are in pure black. Each shape I painted the appropriate color, then finished each with a coat of Mod Podge gloss.

description.text:
CloverPlus v3

This is the next iteration of the CloverPlus mini delta 3D printer design. Most of the CloverPlus v2 parts have been redesigned or significantly changed.

Please see all designs that were used to create this printer in the remix section.

The CloverPlus v3 is a small, mostly-printable 3D printer with delta kinematics. It uses MR9 linear rails with MGN9C rail carriages that attach to 10mm MicroRax or standard 15mm aluminum extrusions. The top and bottom frame parts can be printed either as single parts or as 3 separate parts each, depending on the build volume you have to work with.

All design files (BOM, STLs, OpenSCAD source) are on GitHub; any design files here on Thingiverse are for display purposes only

GitHub repository: https://github.com/mpeterson333/CloverPlus_v3

Time lapse video: https://youtu.be/XVPE6OeyMtI

Please comment if you have any questions or just want to say hi. :)


Printable Diameter: 100mm+
Printable Height(300mm extrusions): 97mm (E3Dv6), 107mm (J-head)
Printable Height(350mm extrusions): 147mm (E3Dv6), 157mm (J-head)
Delta Radius (extrusion sliders): 56.929mm
Delta Radius (MR9 linear rails, 10mm extrusions): 50.929mm
Delta Radius (MR9 linear rails, 15mm extrusions): 51.182mm
Delta Arm Length: 115mm

Note that the 15mm extrusion version delta radius has not yet been tested, but is generated by the same calculation as used for the 10mm extrusion version.

A detailed bill of materials has been provided that lists sources and pricing for all parts, along with some assembly information. Right now there isn't a detailed build guide, but as with v2 I will post details of the trickier aspects of assembly below.

Updates

  • 3/21/2017 - I have the 15mm top and bottom frame parts printed and loosely assembled with 15mm extrusions, but I haven't checked belt alignment yet. The math says it should be okay. :) It may be a while before I find the time to physically test it out. The dual M3 nut plates used with the 10mm microrax extrusions will work with standard 15mm extrusions; links to these are available in the BOM. Because of this I did not modify the extrusion mount mechanism for the 15mm extrusions.
  • 2/11/2017 - Parts compatible with 15mm extrusions have been pushed to github. These include top and bottom frame parts (both one-piece and 3 separate parts versions) along with a new rail carriage belt grip. The 15mm-compatible frame parts are slightly larger than the 10mm parts to accommodate the increased extrusion size without sacrificing build volume. The top pulley and motor mounts have been skewed to account for the wider extrusions and to keep the belt path straight. Also, a hot-end mount for the DeltaPrintr mini hot end has been added. The 15mm extrusion parts have not been tested (I'm reasonably sure they're correct, in that the belt path is good), but the hot end mount has been tested working.
  • 1/14/2017 - The sideways extruder mount was posted to github quite a while back; this works much better for loading filament. I've also been testing carriages and an effector for 10mm balls. This design change makes the printer look better, but so far the new ball size isn't performing as well due to less metal in close proximity to the magnets. I'm experimenting with alternate magnet sizing at the moment; I'll post another update here when I've made some forward progress. I'm still pretty happy with the quality produced by the rails build and all the latest parts. At some point I'd like to tinker with 15mm extrusions as suggested by a commenter; my goal will be to keep dimensions largely the same. We'll see. :)
  • 12/07/2016 - The rails build is now fully up and running and printing very well! A photo of the completed black rails build is now up, as are 2 close up photos of a low-poly crab model I printed with it this morning. I've also added a new bowden tube guide to github (see the rails build photo); this part keeps the bowden tube centered to minimize torque applied to the effector. Finally, I added a new fan shroud for the PG35L extruder source from the TrinityLabs Micro Extruder by ezmobius (thank you!). That thing is now linked in the remix section. I do plan to modify the extruder setup a bit to turn it on its side to make filament loading easier (it's a giant pain right now).

Source

OpenSCAD source is available for all parts on GitHub:

https://github.com/mpeterson333/CloverPlus_v3

Nearly everything is parameterized; it's fairly straight-forward to increase or decrease the size of all parts (for example leg length in the top and bottom frame parts to increase the build area and arm length in the arm parts to match the increased build area). Please ask me in the comments or via msg if you have any questions about the source.

Build Details

See the attached CloverPlus_v3_BOM.ods for part details. Let me know if something is missing or something doesn't make sense.

Build Tips

  • I used 3 M3 x 4mm screws to attach each 250mm MR9 linear rail to its extrusion. More may help with rigidity. A rail stop should be added at the bottom and can be added to the top. The microrax 2-screw extrusion nuts will work at either end to connect both the rail to the extrusion and the railstop to the extrusion.

  • The slider build (NOT RECOMMENDED) uses carriages that are designed to slide smoothly along 10mm MicroRAX extrusions. It can be quite tricky to get these printed so that they slide smoothly, but with a little trial and error it can be done. My carriage slider .stl file works very well with my printing setup (E3D v6 with 0.4mm nozzle and Simply3D slicing at 0.48mm extrusion width, 0.2mm layer height, and 2 perimeters with 50% full honeycomb infill printed at 40mm/s). I have taken time to ensure that my extruder is well-calibrated; I highly recommend this before attempting to print the sliders. I also recommend printing the slide test .stl file before printing any whole slider parts (cloverplus_v3_carriage_slidertest.stl) as it will waste much less plastic as you work to zero in on how much extra spacing you need for smooth sliding. To change the extra spacing in the slider, open up cloverplus_v3_carriage.scad, go to the "Slider extra spacing variables" section, modify slider extra sizing as necessary, and change fittest to 1 to create a smaller fit test piece. Use OpenSCAD to render the updated part and then export it to .stl for printing.

  • The carriage sliders should slide onto the extrusions and be snug yet slide without much effort after working them on and off of an extrusion in all orientations several times. If they're really tough to slide onto the extrusions the first time, then you'er either over-extruding or you need to re-render the part with a slightly higher "slider_extra" value. I had to push pretty hard to get mine on, but I was able to wear them in with some repeat sliding on and off quickly. If they slide too easy, then they're no good, especially if there's absolutely any play at all. In this case you should re-print them with smaller slider extra size variables (see the .scad file). After they're snug but movable, apply some thin oil type lube (I used Superlube thin oil with PTFE) all around each extrusion which should cause them to slide a bit more easily and reduce wear.

  • This design uses 6mm diameter x 10mm long cylindrical N50 magnets. Using anything weaker may be problematic, though you're welcome to try.

  • Clean up the round magnet entry holes in the arms before attempting to jam in the magnets - the new arms are thinner in this area and prone to cracking if mistreated.

  • Extrusion sizing should be at least 300mm; my build uses 350mm. Higher would likely be possible, but watch acceleration and jerk settings as frame rigidity is reduced.

  • The extrusion stepper should have 84oz in of torque or more. Less may result in under- extrusion with PTFE-lined hot ends (E3Dv6 lite, for example) that can't melt plastic as fast as a good all metal hot end (E3Dv6 standard, for example). I use the PG35L geared stepper motor extruder included with the design; this removes torque from the equation.

  • Sand both the plastic and the steel balls / magnets with 120 - 300 grit sandpaper and then clean with alcohol before gluing. I use JB KwikWeld epoxy; it holds well and cures quickly. It can also be scraped off of the balls without too much trouble if you screw up. :) Gorilla glue will work and adhere more strongly, but you'll have to be careful to clamp the balls in place somehow.

  • Make sure the magnets slide all the way back into the arm recesses before gluing via the in the sides of the slots. Test the spacing to ensure the ball does not contact the magnet. Check for wobble where the arm contacts the balls after gluing and clean up the arm ends as needed (this shouldn't be necessary with the new arm design, but double-check anyway).

  • The bed glass in the photos is 120mm in diameter and 3/32" thick (about 2mm), though 115mm would probably work a little better. I cut it with a circle cutter out of a sheet of cheap glass from Lowes. I recommend using glue stick (Elmers purple or extreme) on PET or Kapton tape for printing PETG and PLA without a heated bed. You can apply it straight to the glass, but this will inevitably result in scratched and/or broken glass.

  • I use cork spacers for the motors to reduce vibration and provide some heat insulation. PETG's glass temp is about 85C, but PLA's is much lower at about 65C, so watch your motor temps if you print your frame with PLA.

  • 0.4mm hot end nozzle size or smaller is recommended due to the build volume

  • Firmware setting delta variables are at the top. I highly recommend this delta calibration tool: http://escher3d.com/pages/wizards/wizarddelta.php

  • I recommend a 32-bit Smoothieware or Reprap Firmware based controller board. An 8-bit arduino-based board running Marlin will work, but it will have trouble running at 60mm/s or faster - prints will be rough and the steppers will stutter. Repetier firmware on 8-bit machines is reportedly better suited to delta printers than Marlin, but as I was not able to get my Osoyoo board to correctly stream g-code using Repetier without utterly failing, I can't personally recommend it.

  • For extra pizzazz (higher resolution) with a 32-bit controller, use 0.9degree / step steppers. I used 1.8d/step motors on my CloverPlus builds, but 0.9d steppers don't cost much more and are a good fit for small, highly-detailed prints.

  • Acceleration of 1500mm/s^2 and Junction Deviation of 0.05 (Smoothieware) or Jerk of 10 or lower (Marlin) is a good place to start.

If you have any questions, please ask in the comments! :)

Notes:

This printer was printed with MG Chemicals PETG filament using an E3Dv6 hotend with a 0.4mm nozzle. I strongly recommend PETG for its outstanding strength, minimal shrinkage, and heat tolerance.

I used 3 perimeters for nearly all parts with the exception of the carriage sliders (2 perimeters).

I printed single-piece top and bottom frame parts with my UltiBots 250mm delta printer; if you have the build area, I highly recommend this as it does save a lot of time and a good amount of hardware.

• Streamlined the top and bottom parts and updated for a single 10mm MicroRAX extrusion on each corner; set the multi-part frame connector pieces back slightly to eliminate post-print cleanup for a flush fit

  • Designed new 2-piece carriages that slide smoothly up and down the MicroRAX extrusions; this reduces cost and eliminates linear bearing noise

  • Optional parts to accommodate MR9 linear rails and MGN9C linear rail carriages

  • Changed the arms so they use a triangular profile; this means little to no end cleanup is needed for wobble free operation

  • Relocated the extruder so the bowden tube won't interfere with the carriages

  • Simplified the bed clamps to save about 4mm of vertical space

comments.text: I don't recommend scaling the design up that much. Large format delta printers like that suffer from serious frame rigidity issues. The CPv2 and CPv3 designs generally work well with all plastic frame base and top parts because they're small. At 360mm in diameter the frame would have to be massively thick in order to be rigid enough to avoid major flexing during printing. And for that height you'd want to use much thicker vertical extrusions - 15mm is simply too small. It's significant work to increase the CPv3's extrusion size and in the end it wouldn't be worth the effort. The best approach for large scale deltas is an all metal frame, like this printer: https://www.ultibots.com/d300vs-3d-printer-diy-kit/.

description.text:
I noticed there is lack of tools for aligning Delta printers. We are instead relying on the quality of the print and a prayer for getting the geometry correct. I would like to standardize on a set of tools for validating the physical geometry of deltas is correct. This is the first tool.

This is a concept tool for aligning the Slide Rail carriages on a Kossel Mini. The carriages need to be perfectly parallel to the towers (or slide rails). The mounting holes allow of a small bit of play which can allow the guide rod mounting to not be square with the towers. This directly translates to effector twist. Effector twist will cause a whole host of issues but moist notably poor layer adhesion at extremes and skewing of the print at different points of the bed. You want to minimize effector twist although it can never be 100% eliminated.

How to use:
With the belts removed, the carriage is moved to the bottom of the guide rail.
A 400mm piece of 3.2mm diameter music wire is inserted into the hole that will keep it parallel to the centerline of the carriage. The tools then slides into the G2 belt clamp in the carriage.

Looking at the rod, will show you if it is parallel to the towers since even a minor twist will be exaduarated after 400mm.

Future revisions will be to mount a laser pointer and a target to the slide rails.

This was created using tinkercad

title: Treble Hook Snell/leader Organizer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I like to use treble hook snells for fishing. A snell has the line already attached to it. So you can get hook bonnets for the hooks, but the line still seems to go everywhere. So I designed this to have a spot for the fishing line to wrap around the bonnet so things don't get all tangled up in my tackle box.

So the idea is that you slip the line end of your snell/leader into the top and pull it through until the treble hook rests in the slots for it. Then you wrap the line around the ring in the edge. I'm going to eventually make a small slot to tuck the end of the line into OR more probably just design and print a ring or and end cap which slips over the end.

My wive also uses these to keep the treble hook lines that she uses for crawdad fishing organized.

So now I'm on r2. I've made some changes. I made the center hole larger to accommodate the shank and eyelets of larger treble hooks. I made the grooves for the hooks deeper. I made the string wrapping groove smaller. I increased the diameter of the whole base by 2mm to accommodate larger treble hooks. I also included an end cap so that the whole thing doesn't unravel.
